&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Maxwell&amp;#39;s equation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Maxwell&amp;#39;s equations&lt;/strong&gt; are a set of four fundamental equations that describe how &lt;strong&gt;electric and magnetic fields&lt;/strong&gt; are generated and altered by each other and by charges and currents.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These equations were formulated by &lt;strong&gt;James Clerk Maxwell&lt;/strong&gt; in the mid-19th century.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They provide a comprehensive theoretical foundation for &lt;strong&gt;classical electromagnetism, optics, and electric circuits&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Maxwell&amp;#39;s equations predict that &lt;strong&gt;electric and magnetic fields propagate as waves&lt;/strong&gt; moving at the speed of light, establishing the &lt;strong&gt;electromagnetic nature of light&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These equations unify the concepts of &lt;strong&gt;electricity, magnetism, and light&lt;/strong&gt; into a single theoretical framework.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s equation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/strong&gt; states that the current through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the &lt;strong&gt;voltage&lt;/strong&gt; across the two points.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is usually formulated as &lt;strong&gt;V = IR&lt;/strong&gt;, where V is the voltage, I is the current, and R is the resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Laplace equation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Laplace equation&lt;/strong&gt; is a second-order partial differential equation named after Pierre-Simon Laplace.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used in &lt;strong&gt;electrostatics, fluid dynamics, and heat conduction&lt;/strong&gt; to describe the behavior of scalar fields.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kirchhoff&amp;#39;s equation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kirchhoff&amp;#39;s circuit laws&lt;/strong&gt; are two equalities that deal with the current and potential difference in the lumped element model of electrical circuits.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They include &lt;strong&gt;Kirchhoff&amp;#39;s current law (KCL)&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Kirchhoff&amp;#39;s voltage law (KVL)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Liquids do not have fixed volume&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Liquids have no fixed shape and take the shape of the container in which they are kept.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Liquids are able to flow and change shape easily.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike gases, liquids have a definite volume that does not change under normal conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The molecules in a liquid are closely packed but not in fixed positions, allowing them to move around each other.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Liquids exhibit properties like surface tension and viscosity, which are related to the cohesive forces between their molecules.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gases&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gases have neither a fixed shape nor a fixed volume.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They expand to fill the shape and volume of their container.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The molecules in gases are much farther apart compared to liquids and move freely at high speeds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solids&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Solids have both a fixed shape and a fixed volume.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The molecules in solids are closely packed in a regular arrangement and can only vibrate in place.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They do not flow and maintain their shape under normal conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plasma&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plasma is a state of matter similar to gas but consists of charged particles (ions and electrons).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is found in stars, including the sun, and is created at very high temperatures.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plasma conducts electricity and is affected by magnetic fields.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;John Newlands&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;In 1866, &lt;strong&gt;John Newlands, an English scientist, &lt;/strong&gt;arranged the then-known elements in order of increasing atomic mass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;He started with the element with the lowest atomic mass (hydrogen) and ended with &lt;strong&gt;Thorium&lt;/strong&gt; which was the&lt;strong&gt; 56th element.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;He found that every eighth element has the same properties as the first. He compared it to the octave found in music.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;That&amp;#39;s why he called it the&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;law of octaves&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;This is known as&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Newlands&amp;#39; Law of Octaves&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The properties of lithium and sodium were found to be similar in Newlands&amp;#39; octave.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;It was assumed by &lt;strong&gt;Newlands that only 56 elements&lt;/strong&gt; existed in nature and no more elements would be discovered in the future.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;But, later on, several new elements were discovered, whose properties did not fit into the Law of Octaves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;In &lt;strong&gt;1869&lt;/strong&gt;, just five years after &lt;strong&gt;John Newlands &lt;/strong&gt;put forward his Law of Octaves, a Russian chemist called &lt;strong&gt;Dmitri Mendeleev published a periodic table.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mendeleev&lt;/strong&gt; also arranged the elements known at the time in order of &lt;strong&gt;relative atomic mass&lt;/strong&gt;, but he did some other things that made his table much more successful.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Marie Curie &lt;/strong&gt;is best remembered for discovering radium and polonium, and for her huge contribution to finding treatments for cancer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;In 1829, &lt;strong&gt;Johann D&amp;ouml;bereiner grouped the elements with similar chemical properties into clusters of three called &amp;#39;Triads&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;D&amp;ouml;bereiner invented the first lighter&lt;/strong&gt;, which was known as the &lt;strong&gt;D&amp;ouml;bereiner&amp;#39;s lamp.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;to involve the community in forest conservation efforts&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Chipko Movement was a forest conservation movement in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It began in the 1970s in the Himalayan region of Uttarakhand (then part of Uttar Pradesh).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The movement is known for the active participation of local communities, especially women, in protecting forests.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The term &amp;quot;Chipko&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;to hug&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;to cling,&amp;quot; reflecting the method of embracing trees to prevent their felling.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The movement highlighted the importance of forests in the environment and the role of local communities in forest management.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental Impact&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Chipko Movement emphasized the ecological importance of forests for soil conservation, water regulation, and climate moderation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It brought attention to the adverse effects of deforestation on the environment and local livelihoods.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Women&amp;#39;s Role&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Women played a crucial role in the Chipko Movement, demonstrating their dependence on forests for fuel, fodder, and water.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The movement empowered women and highlighted their role in environmental conservation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Global Influence&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Chipko Movement inspired similar environmental movements globally, emphasizing the need for community involvement in conservation efforts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It has been recognized as a pioneering effort in the field of environmental activism and sustainable development.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parabolic path&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A body projected into the air with a certain angle follows a &lt;strong&gt;parabolic path&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is due to the influence of &lt;strong&gt;gravity&lt;/strong&gt;, which causes the body to accelerate downwards.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The initial velocity and angle of projection determine the &lt;strong&gt;shape and range&lt;/strong&gt; of the parabolic path.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the absence of air resistance, the only force acting on the body is &lt;strong&gt;gravity&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The path is symmetric, meaning the time to reach the peak is equal to the time to descend back to the original height.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Linear path&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This type of path is followed when there is no acceleration acting on the body, such as in a vacuum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Spherical path&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This path is followed by objects moving in circular orbits, like satellites around a planet.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Elliptical path&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This path is typically followed by celestial objects like planets and comets orbiting a star.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Phosphorus is also vital for early growth, particularly in root development and energy transfer within the plant. &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, option 4 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Role of Phosphorus in Early Growth&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stimulates Root Development&lt;/strong&gt;: Phosphorus promotes strong root systems, which are critical during the early stages of plant growth.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy Transfer: &lt;/strong&gt;Phosphorus is a component of ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the energy currency of cells, supporting various metabolic processes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Seedling Growth:&lt;/strong&gt; Essential for early establishment, as it enhances the strength of young plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sources of Phosphorus in Fertilizers&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Single Superphosphate (SSP).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Diammonium Phosphate (DAP).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Bone Meal (organic source).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complementary Roles&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Nitrogen stimulates vegetative growth (leaves and stems).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Phosphorus primarily boosts early growth by focusing on root and overall plant energy needs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, phosphorus is indeed a key component for stimulating early-stage growth, particularly through strong root development and energy facilitation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Blue, Green, Yellow and Orange&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When white light passes through a prism, it gets dispersed into its constituent colors, forming a spectrum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sequence of colors from one end of the spectrum to the other is typically remembered by the acronym &amp;quot;VIBGYOR&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each color in the spectrum corresponds to a different wavelength, with violet having the shortest wavelength and red the longest.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct sequence of colors as observed in the spectrum is Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, and Red (VIBGYOR).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dispersion of Light:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Dispersion occurs because different colors of light travel at different speeds when passing through a medium like glass.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This phenomenon is responsible for the formation of a rainbow and the splitting of white light through a prism.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prism:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A prism is a transparent optical element with flat, polished surfaces that refract light.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Prisms can be used to break light up into its constituent spectral colors (the colors of the rainbow).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refraction:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one medium to another with a different density.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This bending causes the light to change speed and direction, leading to phenomena like dispersion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wavelengths of Visible Light:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Visible light ranges from approximately 380 nm (violet) to 700 nm (red).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each color within this range has a specific wavelength, which determines its position in the spectrum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
